[Atlas Mountains]] (Idurar n Wa\u1e6dlas), North and Western [[Sahara]]\n***[[Eastern Berber languages|Eastern Berbers]]\n****[[Nafusa people|Nafusa]]: [[Nafusa Mountains]] (Drar n infusen), [[Tripolitania]], northwestern [[Libya]]\n****[[Zuwara Berber|Zuwara]]: [[Zuwara]], coast of western [[Tripolitania]] in northwestern [[Libya]].\n****[[Matmata Berber|Matmata]]: [[Matmata, Tunisia|Matm\u00e2ta]], southern [[Tunisia]]\n****[[Djerbi language|Djerba]] Berbers: [[Djerba Island]], southern [[Tunisia]] coast\n****[[Sokna, Libya|Sokna]] Berbers: [[Sokna, Libya|Sokna]] Oasis (Isuknan), [[Fezzan]], north central [[Libya]], [[Sahara]]\n****[[Awjila language|Awjila]]: [[Awjila]] oasis, [[Cyrenaica]], eastern [[Libya]], [[Sahara]]\n****[[Ghadam\u00e8s language|Ghadam\u00e8s]]: [[Ghadam\u00e8s]] Oasis, Western [[Libya]], [[Sahara]]\n***[[Northern Berber languages|Northern Berbers]]\n****[[Kabyles]] (Iqvayliyen): [[Kabylie]] (Tamurt n Iqvayliyen), Mediterranean coast of northern [[Algeria]]\n****[[Zenati language |Zenati]] (Iznaten/Iznasen) speakers: regions in [[Algeria]] and [[Morocco]]\n*****[[Mozabites]] (At Mzab): [[M'zab|Mzab]] region, northern [[Sahara]], north central [[Algeria]]\n*****[[Shawiya people|Shawiya]] (I\u0161awiyen): [[Aur\u00e8s Mountains]] ([[Aur\u00e8s Mountains|Idurar n Awras]]), northeastern [[Algeria]]\n*****[[Chenouas|Shenwa]] (Ichenwiyen): west-central mountains of northwestern [[Algeria]]\n*****[[Riffians]] (Irifiyen):  [[Rif]], [[Rif Mountains]] (Arrif), northern [[Morocco]]\n*****[[Sanhaja]] (I\u1e93nagen/I\u1e93najen) peoples: regions in Middle West [[Atlas mountains]] and Eastern [[Morocco]]\n*****[[Masmuda]] peoples: regions in Northern and Western Morocco\n******[[Ghomaras|Ghomara]]: Far West [[Rif Mountains]] (Arrif), Northern [[Morocco]]\n******[[Shilha people|Shilha]] (Shl\u1e25i): West [[Atlas mountains]], Western [[Morocco]]\n*[[Haratin]]: Indigenous population of the Maghreb and Sahara of uncertain origin; members now speak either [[Berber languages]] or [[Arabic languages|Arabic]]; inhabit [[Morocco]], [[Mauritania]], [[Western Sahara]], [[Algeria]].\n\n==== Nile Valley ====\n*[[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]] speakers\n**[[Egyptian language|Egyptian]] speakers\n[[File:Women in Egypt.jpg|thumb|[[Egyptians|Egyptian]] women in traditional dress]]\n***[[Copts]] (Rem en Kh\u0113mi/Rem en K\u0113me): [[Egypt]], a Christian, largely non-Arabized Egyptian people directly descended from [[Ancient Egyptians]]\n**[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] speakers\n***[[Beja people|Beja]]: Northeastern [[Sudan]], between [[Red Sea]] coast and almost to the [[Nile River]] ([[White Nile]] and [[Blue Nile]]) eastern banks, Far Northwest [[Eritrea]], [[Sahara]] [[Eastern Desert]], Far Southeast [[Egypt]]\n**[[Berber languages|Berber]] speakers\n***[[Siwi people|Siwi Berbers]]: [[Siwa Oasis]] (Isiwan), western [[Egypt]], [[Sahara]]\n*[[Niger-Congo languages|Niger-Congo]] speakers\n**[[Nuba peoples|Nuba]] peoples: [[Sudan]], [[Nuba Hills]]\n***[[Katla languages|Katla]]-[[Rashad languages|Rashad]] peoples: [[Sudan]], [[Nuba Hills]]\n***[[Talodi languages|Talodi]]-[[Heiban languages|Heiban]] peoples: [[Sudan]], [[Nuba Hills]]\n[[File:Peace agreement dancers in Kapoeta, Sudan.jpg|thumb|right|[[Nilotic peoples|Nilotic]] men in [[Kapoeta]], [[South Sudan]].]]\n**[[Serer people|Serer]] - current habit [[Senega]], [[Gambia]], [[Mauritania]]\n*[[Nilo-Saharan languages|Nilo-Saharan]] speakers\n**[[Eastern Sudanic languages|Eastern Sudanic]] speakers\n***[[Northern Eastern Sudanic languages|Northern Eastern Sudanic]] ([[Astaboran languages|Astaboran]]) peoples  \n****[[Nubian languages|Nubian]] speakers\n*****[[Nubians]]: Far Northern [[North Sudan]] and Far Southern [[Egypt]], along middle [[Nile river]] valley banks \n***[[Southern Eastern Sudanic languages|Southern Eastern Sudanic]] ([[Kir-Abbaian languages|Kir-Abbaian]]) peoples\n****[[Nilotic]] peoples \n*****[[Dinka-Nuer]] peoples\n******[[Dinka people|Dinka]] (Jieng): mainly in [[Lakes State|Lakes]], [[Warrap State|Warrap]] and [[Unity State|Unity]] States, Upper [[Nile river]] course, Central and North [[South Sudan]].\n******[[Nuer people|Nuer]] (Naadh): mainly in [[Jonglei State]], East of Upper [[Nile river]] course, East Central [[South Sudan]].\n*****[[Luo peoples]]\n******[[Anuak people|Anuak]] (Anywaa): mainly East [[Jonglei State]], East [[South Sudan]], and also mainly in [[Gambela Region]], Lowlands of Far Southwest [[Ethiopia]] (border areas between [[South Sudan]] and [[Ethiopia]]).\n******[[Shilluk people|Shilluk]] (Chollo/C\u00f8ll\u00f8): mainly in North [[South Sudan]], west of the Upper [[Nile river]] course, [[Upper Nile State]], [[South Sudan]] ([[Kodok]] or [[Kodok|Kothok]], formerly known as [[Fashoda]] is in their territory).\n**[[Fur language|Fur]] speakers\n***[[Fur people|Fur]] (F\u00f2\u00f2r\u00e0): [[Darfur]], Western [[Sudan]]\n**[[Maban languages|Maban]] speakers\n***[[Masalit people|Masalit]]: [[Darfur]], Western [[Sudan]]\n**[[Kadu languages|Kadu]] peoples: [[Sudan]], [[Nuba Hills]]\n**[[Saharan languages|Saharan]] speakers\n***[[Toubou people|Toubou]]: [[Chad]]\n\n==== Southern Africa ====\n[[File:Jong Zoeloekryger 1860.jpg|thumb|19th century Zulu man wearing a warrior's garb|alt=|213px]]\n[[File:Singing-for-Mokhibo-Lesotho.jpg|thumb|Sotho women wearing the traditional ''Seana Marena'' blanket.|269x269px]]\n[[File:Mozambique001.jpg|thumb|Makua mother and child|alt=|213px]]\n\n*[[Bantu languages]] speaking peoples of [[Southern Africa]]: [[South Africa]], [[Lesotho]], [[Eswatini]], [[Botswana]], [[Mozambique]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Namibia]], southern [[Angola]].\n**[[Nguni people]]\n***[[Xhosa people|Xhosa]]\n***[[Zulu people|Zulu]]\n***Ndebele\n****[[Northern Ndebele people]] (Zimbabwe)\n****[[Southern Ndebele people]] (South Africa)\n*****[[Southern Ndebele language|South Ndebele]]\n*****[[Sumayela Ndebele language|Sumayela Ndebele]]\n***[[Swazi people|Swati]]\n***[[Phuthi language|Phuthi]]\n***[[Lala language (South Africa)|Lala]]\n***[[Bhaca people|Bhaca]]\n***[[Hlubi people|Hlubi]]\n***[[Nhlangwini language|Nhlangwini]]\n**[[Sotho\u2013Tswana]] people\n***[[Tswana people|Tswana]]\n***[[Bobirwa]]\n***[[Tswapong people|Tswapong]]\n***[[Kgalagadi language|Kgalagadi]]\n***[[Sotho people|Sotho]]\n***[[Pedi people|Northern Sotho]]\n***East Sotho (Pulana, Khutswe and Pai)\n***[[Lozi people|Lozi]]\n**[[Makua people]]\n***[[Makhuwa language|Makhuwa]] \n***[[Koti language|Koti]]\n***[[Sakati language|Sakati]] (Nathembo)\n***[[Lomwe language|Lomwe]]\n***[[Chuwabu language|Chuwabu]]\n***[[Moniga language|Moniga]]\n**[[Tswa\u2013Ronga]] languages people\n***[[Tsonga people|Tsonga]]\n***[[Ronga people|Ronga]]\n***[[Tswa people|Tswa]]\n**[[Venda people]]\n**[[Shona people]]\n**[[Chopi people]]\n***[[Chopi language|Chopi]]\n***[[Guitonga language (Mozambique)|Guitonga]]\n**[[Chewa people]]\n**[[Yeyi people]]\n**[[Kavango \u2013 Southwest Bantu languages|Kavango]] languages people\n***[[Ovambo people]]\n***[[Herero people]]\n***[[Kavango people]]\n\n*[[Khoisan languages|Southern Khoikhoi languages]] speaking peoples: Angola, Namibia, Botswana, [[Kalahari desert]], Zimbabwe, west and southwestern South Africa.\n**[[Khoikhoi]]\n**[[Nama people|Nama]] ([[Namaqua peoples|Namaqua]])\n**[[Damara people|Damara]] [[File:Damara man.jpg|thumb|Damara man wearing the \u01c3g\u016bb, a traditional attire.|alt=|213px]]\n**[[Hai\u01c1om people|Hai\u01c1om]]\n**[[Gana and Gwi people|G\u01c0u and G\u01c1ana]]\n**Naro\n**Tsoa/Tshwa/Kua\n*[[Khoisan languages|Southern San languages]] speaking peoples: Angola, Namibia, Botswana, Kalahari desert, west and southwestern South Africa.\n**Kx'a/Ju\u2013\u01c2Hoan\n***[[\u01c3Kung people|\u01c3Kung]]/Juu\n****\u01c2\u02bcAmkoe\n****\u01c2Kx\u02bcao-\u01c1\u02bcae (Auen)\n**Tuu\n**\u01c3Kwi (!Ui)\n***\u01c0Xam\n***\u01c2Khomani (N\u01c0u)\n***Khwe (Khoi, Kxoe)\n**Taa\n***\u01c3Xoo\u014bake/N\u01c0umde\n\n==== West Africa ====\n*[[Niger-Congo languages|Niger-Congo]] speakers\n**[[Dogon people|Dogon]]: Far Southeastern [[Mali]] and Far Northwestern [[Burkina Faso]]\n**[[Senegambian languages|Senegambian]] speakers\n***[[Fula-Serer languages|Fula-Serer]] speakers\n****[[Serer people|Serer]] ([[Serer people|S\u00e9r\u00e8re]]): [[Senegal]], the [[Gambia]], [[Mauritania]], [[Western Sahara]]\n**[[Benue-Congo]] peoples [[File:Kwarastatedrummers.jpg|thumb|[[Yoruba music|Yoruba]] [[drum]]mers|213px]]\n***[[Cross River languages|Cross River]] peoples\n****[[Ogoni people|Ogoni]]: [[Nigeria]]\n**[[Ijoid languages|Ijo]] peoples\n***[[Ijaw people|Ijaw]]/[[Ijo people|Ijo]] people: in the [[Niger delta]] region, southern [[Nigeria]].\n****[[Itsekiri]] people: in the Niger delta region \n**[[Kwa languages|Kwa]] peoples\n***[[Potou-Tano languages|Potou-Tano]] peoples\n****[[Ashanti people|Ashanti]]: [[Ghana]]\n**[[Volta-Niger languages|Volta-Niger]] peoples\n***[[YEAI]]\n****[[Igbo people|Igbo]] ([[\u1e46\u0301d\u1ecb\u0301 \u00ccgb\u00f2]]): [[Nigeria]]\n****[[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] ([[Yoruba people|\u00c0w\u1ecdn \u1eccm\u1ecd Yor\u00f9b\u00e1]]): [[Nigeria]]\n**[[Chadic languages|Chadic]] speakers\n***[[Hausa people|Hausa]]: [[Nigeria]], [[Chad]], [[Sudan]]\n*[[Nilo-Saharan languages|Nilo-Saharan]] speakers\n**[[Fur people|Fur]] ([[Fur people|F\u00f2\u00f2r\u00e0]]): [[Darfur]], Western [[Sudan]]\n\n=== Eurasia ===\n==== Asia ====\n===== Middle East =====\n[[File:Marsh Arabs in a mashoof.jpg|thumb|[[Marsh Arabs|Marsh Arabs/Ma'dan]] poling a ''[[mashoof]]'' in the Mesopotamian Marshes]]\n[[File:Assyrianzakho.JPG|thumb|An [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] woman wearing [[Assyrian clothing|traditional clothing]], [[Zakho]].]]\n[[File:DRUSE RESIDENTS OF THE CARMEL FEAST ON A MEAL OF TRADITIONAL FOODS. COLOR PHOTO TAKEN IN THE LATE 19TH CENTURY BY FRENCH PHOTOGRAPHER, BONFILS. \u05e6\u05d9\u05dc\u05d5\u05dd \u05e6\u05d1\u05e2 \u05de\u05e1\u05d5\u05e3 \u05d4\u05de\u05d0\u05d4 \u05d419 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e6\u05dc\u05dd.jpg|thumb|[[Druze people|Druze]] residents of [[Mount Carmel]] ]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 44792 Tisha BAv at the Western Wall.JPG|thumb|[[Jewish people|Jewish]] man praying during [[Tisha B'Av]] at the [[Western Wall]] ]]\n[[File:Samaritans on Mount Gerizim, West Bank - 20060429.jpg|thumb|[[Samaritans]] on [[Mount Gerizim]] ]]\n[[File:Animated conversation (6408248573).jpg|thumb|[[Soqotri people|Soqotri]] men]]\n\n*[[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]] languages\n**[[Semitic peoples]]\n***[[East Semitic]] peoples\n****[[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] (\u0100\u1e6f\u016br\u0101y\u0113/S\u016br\u0101y\u0113/S\u016bry\u0101y\u0113): A Christian [[Neo-Aramaic]] speaking people indigenous to [[northern Iraq]] (which was once part of [[Assyria]], [[Asuristan]]), southeastern [[Turkey]] and northwest of [[Iran]] in [[Upper Mesopotamia]], but have also traditionally lived in northeast [[Syria]], albeit recently. There is a testified historical continuity between old [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] and modern Assyrians for the majority of people in the same land that they lived since Antiquity before [[Arabization]] of [[Iraq]]: [[Northern Mesopotamia]] that corresponds with old [[Assyria]] (originally they were speakers of the [[Akkadian language]] but in Antiquity, by the end of the 1st millennium BC, [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] adopted the [[Aramaic]] language from the [[Aramaeans]] and at present time they speak [[Assyrian Neo-Aramaic]]). However, not all modern Assyrians identify as such, and several are from peoples that adopted an Assyrian ethnic identity (see [[Terms for Syriac Christians]]).<ref name=\"UNPO\">Unrepresented Nations and People Organization | UNPO, ''Assyrians the Indigenous People of Iraq'' [http://www.unpo.org/article/2560]</ref>\n***[[West Semitic languages|West Semitic]] peoples\n****[[Central Semitic]] peoples\n*****[[Arabic peoples]]\n******[[Bedouin]] (Badaw\u012b) of the interior deserts of [[Arabian desert|Arabia]] and [[Syrian desert|Syria]].\n******[[Druze people|Druze]] (Al-Muwa\u1e25\u1e25id\u016bn/Al-Muwa\u1e25\u1e25id\u012bn/Ahl al-Taw\u1e25\u012bd): of [[Jabal al-Druze]], [[Syria]], [[Lebanon]], [[Jordan]] and [[Israel]]. The faith of the Druze is a blend of [[Islam]]'s [[Ismailism]], [[Judaism]], [[Christianity]], [[Neoplatonism]], [[Pythagoreanism]], [[Gnosticism]] and [[Greek philosophy]]. The foundational text of the faith is the [[Epistles of Wisdom]]. Even though they have been a minority for their entire history, they have played a significant role in shaping the history of the [[Levant]]. Although the faith originally developed out of [[Ismaili Islam]], Druze are usually not considered Muslims. The oldest and most densely-populated Druze communities exist in [[Mount Lebanon]] and in the south of Syria around [[Jabal al-Druze]] (literally the \"Mountain of the Druze\").\n******[[Marsh Arabs|Marsh Dwellers]]/[[Marsh Arabs]] (Ma'dan/\u02bbArab al-Ahw\u0101r): An Arabic-speaking people living in the [[Mesopotamian Marshes|marshes of southern Iraq]] or on the Iranian side of the [[Shatt al-Arab]].<ref>Sawahla & Dloomy (2007, pp. 425\u2013433)</ref>\n*****[[Northwest Semitic]] peoples\n******[[Arameans]] (\u0100ramay\u0113): Central and Western [[Syria]], ancient land of the [[Aramaeans]] ([[Aram (biblical region)|Aram]]) in the [[Levant]], an [[Western Neo-Aramaic|Aramaic]]-speaking people that descends from ancient [[Aramaeans]]. In recent years, there has been an attempt to revive [[Western Neo-Aramaic|Western Aramaic]] among [[Arameans in Israel|Aramean Christians]] living in the [[State of Israel|Israeli]] village of [[Jish]].\n******[[Canaanites|Canaanite peoples]]\n*******[[Jews]] (Yehudim): along with [[Samaritans]], belong to the [[Israelite]] nation of the southern Levant, who are believed by archaeologists and historians to have branched out of the Canaanite peoples and culture through the development of a distinct monolatrous\u2014and later monotheistic\u2014religion centered on El/Yahweh,<ref>Tubb, 1998. pg 13\u201314.</ref><ref>Mark Smith, in ''The Early History of God: Yahweh and Other Deities of Ancient Israel'', states \"Despite the long regnant model that the Canaanites and Israelites were people of fundamentally different culture, archaeological data now casts doubt on this view. The material culture of the region exhibits numerous common points between Israelites and Canaanites in the Iron I period (c. 1200\u20131000 BC). The record would suggest that the Israelite culture largely overlapped with and derived from Canaanite culture. ... In short, Israelite culture was largely Canaanite in nature. Given the information available, one cannot maintain a radical cultural separation between Canaanites and Israelites for the Iron I period.\" (pp. 6\u20137). Smith, Mark (2002) ''The Early History of God: Yahweh and Other Deities of Ancient Israel'' (Eerdman's)</ref><ref>Rendsberg, Gary (2008). \"Israel without the Bible\". In Frederick E. Greenspahn. ''The Hebrew Bible: New Insights and Scholarship''. NYU Press, pp. 3\u20135</ref> one of the Ancient Canaanite deities. Following the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] colonial occupation, destruction of [[Herod's Temple]], and failed Jewish revolts, most Jews were either expelled, taken as slaves to Rome, or massacred,<ref>[[Josephus]]. [http://sacred-texts.com/jud/josephus/war-6.htm War of the Jews] 9:2.</ref> although a small number of Jews managed to remain over the centuries despite persecution by the various conquerors of the region, including the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], [[Arabs]], [[Ottomans]], and the [[United Kingdom|British]]. Additionally, a substantial number of Jews returned from [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]] during the 19th and 20th centuries (mainly under the Zionist movement), as well as after the modern State of [[Israel]] was established in 1948. This was coupled with the [[Revival of the Hebrew language|revival of Hebrew]], the only [[Canaanite language]] still spoken today. DNA studies show that all major diaspora Jewish communities, with the exception of Ethiopian and Yemenite Jews, derive the majority of their ancestry from [[ancient Israelites]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.khazaria.com/genetics/abstracts.html |title = Jewish Genetics - DNA, genes, Jews, Ashkenazi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1003316 |pmid=23468648|pmc=3585000|title=Genome-Wide Diversity in the Levant Reveals Recent Structuring by Culture|journal=PLOS Genetics|volume=9|issue=2 |pages=e1003316|year=2013|last1=Haber|first1=Marc|last2=Gauguier|first2=Dominique|last3=Youhanna|first3=Sonia|last4=Patterson|first4=Nick|last5=Moorjani|first5=Priya|last6=Botigu\u00e9|first6=Laura R|last7=Platt|first7=Daniel E|last8=Matisoo-Smith|first8=Elizabeth|last9=Soria-Hernanz|first9=David F|last10=Wells|first10=R. Spencer|last11=Bertranpetit |first11=Jaume|last12=Tyler-Smith|first12=Chris|last13=Comas|first13=David|last14=Zalloua|first14=Pierre A}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1038/nature09103| pmid=20531471| title=The genome-wide structure of the Jewish people| journal=Nature| volume=466| issue=7303| pages=238\u2013242| year=2010| last1=Behar| first1=Doron M.| last2=Yunusbayev| first2=Bayazit| last3=Metspalu| first3=Mait| last4=Metspalu| first4=Ene| last5=Rosset| first5=Saharon| last6=Parik| first6=J\u00fcri| last7=Rootsi| first7=Siiri| last8=Chaubey| first8=Gyaneshwer| last9=Kutuev| first9=Ildus| last10=Yudkovsky| first10=Guennady| last11=Khusnutdinova| first11=Elza K.| last12=Balanovsky| first12=Oleg| last13=Semino| first13=Ornella| last14=Pereira| first14=Luisa| last15=Comas| first15=David| last16=Gurwitz| first16=David| last17=Bonne-Tamir| first17=Batsheva| last18=Parfitt| first18=Tudor| last19=Hammer| first19=Michael F.| last20=Skorecki| first20=Karl| last21=Villems| first21=Richard| bibcode=2010Natur.466..238B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2010/06/tracing-roots-jewishness | title=Tracing the Roots of Jewishness| date=2010-06-03}}</ref>\n*******[[Samaritans]] ([[Samaritans|Samerim]]): of [[Samaria]]. An ethno-religious group of the Levant, closely related [[Genetic studies on Jews|genetically]] and culturally to the [[Jewish diaspora]] and are understood to have branched off from the latter around the time of the [[Assyrian exile]]. The Samaritans are adherents of [[Samaritanism]], an [[Abrahamic religion]] closely related to [[Judaism]]. Their sole norm of religious observance is the [[Samaritan Pentateuch]].<ref name=\"UNHCR\">The UN Refugee Agency | UNHCR, ''World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples'' [http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/topic,463af2212,49709ee42,49749cd028,0,,,.html]</ref><ref name=\"Samaritans and Other Israeli Populations\">\nDepartment of Evolutionary Biology at University of Tartu Estonian Biocentre | Reconstruction of Patrilineages and Matrilineages of Samaritans and Other Israeli Populations From Y-Chromosome and Mitochondrial DNA Sequence Variation, ''Molecular Anthropology Group'' [http://evolutsioon.ut.ee/publications/Shen2004.pdf]</ref>\n****[[South Semitic languages|South Semitic]] speakers\n*****[[Eastern South Semitic]] speakers\n******[[Bathari]] people: [[Dhofar]], Southern [[Oman]]. Descendants from the original people of [[Dhofar]] before [[Arabization]].\n******[[Harasis]]: [[Jiddat al-Harasis]], Central [[Oman]]. Descendants from the original people of [[South Arabia]] before [[Arabization]].\n******[[Hoby\u00f3t]] people: [[Dhofar]], Southern [[Oman]], Far Eastern [[Yemen]]. Descendants from the original people of [[Dhofar]] before [[Arabization]].\n******[[Mehri people|Mehris]]: [[Al Mahrah]], Eastern [[Yemen]], [[Dhofar]], Southern [[Oman]]. Descendants from the original people of [[Dhofar]] before [[Arabization]].\n******[[Shehri language|Shehri]] people/[[Jibbali]] people: [[Dhofar]], Southern [[Oman]]. Descendants from the original people of [[Dhofar]] before [[Arabization]].\n******[[Soqotri]] people: [[Soqotra]] island and group of islands, southeast of mainland [[Yemen]], [[Indian Ocean]]. Descendants from the original natives of [[South Arabia]] before [[Arabization]].\n\n[[File:Armenianwomendiyarbakir.jpg|thumb|[[Armenian people|Armenian]] women in [[Diyarbak\u0131r]]]]\n[[File:Diyarbekir shepherd, Mardin Kurd, Aljazeera Kurd, 1873.jpg|thumb|[[Kurdish people|Kurds]] wearing [[Kurdish clothing|traditional clothing]]]]\n[[File:Yezidi New Year festival at Lalish (18 April 2017) 11.jpg|thumb|[[Yazidi]] festival at [[Lalish]] ]]\n[[File:Men in Zaranj-cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Baloch people|Baloch]] of [[Nimruz Province]], Afghanistan]]\n\n*[[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] speakers\n**[[Armenians]] ([[Armenians|Hayer]]): The Christian Armenian people were the original inhabitants of what is now modern Eastern Turkey,  specifically around [[Lake Van]] and the biblical mountain of [[Mount Ararat|Ararat]] and spoke the [[Western Armenian]] language. Since the [[Armenian Genocide]] in which up to 1,500,000 people perished, the number of the original Armenian inhabitants is almost non-existent and they have since been replaced with ethnic Turks and Kurds.\n**[[Iranian peoples]]\n***[[East Iranian]] peoples\n****[[Northeast Iranian]] peoples\n*****[[Ossetians]] (Ir\u00e6\u0442\u0442\u00e6): [[South Ossetia]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], Southern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[West Iranian]] peoples\n****[[Caspian languages|Caspian]]/[[Caspian languages|South Caspian]] peoples\n*****[[Gilaks]]: [[Gilan]], North [[Iran]], South [[Caspian Sea]] coast and [[Elburz]] Mountains\n*****[[Mazanderani people|Mazanderanis]]/[[Mazanderani people|Mazanis]]/[[Mazanderani people|Tabaris]]: [[Mazanderan]], [[Tabaristan]], Northern [[Iran]], South [[Caspian Sea]] coast and [[Elburz]] Mountains\n****[[Northwest Iranian]] peoples\n*****Northwestern I\n******[[Kurds]] (Kurd/Kurmandzh): [[Kurdistan]], Northwestern and Western [[Iran]], Northern [[Iraq]], Northeast and Northern [[Syria]], Southeast [[Turkey]], [[Zagros]] and East [[Anatolian Plateau]]\n*******[[Yazidis]] (\u00cazid\u00ee): [[Nineveh Governorate]], Northern [[Iraq]]\n******[[Lak people (Iran)]]: Southwestern [[Iran]], [[Zagros]] Mountains\n******[[Zaza-Gorani]] peoples\n*******[[Shabaks]]: [[Sinjar]] District of the [[Nineveh Governorate]] in northern [[Iraq]].\n*******[[Zaza People|Zazas]]: Southeastern Turkey, Upper [[Euphrates]] river, East [[Anatolian Plateau]]\n*****Northwestern II\n******[[Baluchi people|Baluchis]] (Baloch/Baluch): [[Baluchistan]], Southeastern [[Iran]], Southwestern [[Pakistan]], Extreme Southern [[Afghanistan]]\n******Tatic peoples\n*******[[Talysh people|Talysh]] (Talyshon): Northwestern [[Iran]], Far South [[Azerbaijan]], South [[Caspian Sea]] coast and [[Elburz]] Mountains\n*******[[Tats (Iran)]]/[[Tats (Iran)|South Tats]] (Ir\u00fcn\u0259 T\u00e2t\u00fcn): Northwest [[Iran]]\n****[[Southwestern Iranian languages|Southwest Iranian]] peoples\n*****Larestani\u2013Gulf peoples\n******[[Kumzari people|Kumzaris]]: Northern [[Musandam Governorate|Musandam]], [[Oman]]\n*****Lurs and Bakhtiaris\n******[[Lurs]] (Lur): [[Luristan]], Western and Southwestern [[Iran]], [[Zagros]] Mountains\n******[[Bakhtiari people|Bakhtiaris]] (Bakhtiar): Southwestern [[Iran]], [[Zagros]]\n*****[[Persian people]]: [[Iran]]\n*****[[Tat people (Caucasus)|Tats (Caucasus)]]: [[Republic of Azerbaijan]], [[Dagestan]] ([[Russia]])\n\n===== Caucasus =====\n[[File:Adyghe Costumes.jpg|thumb|Traditional [[Adyghe people|Adyghe]] clothing.]]\n\n{{Main|Peoples of the Caucasus}}\n\n*Indo-European peoples\n**[[Armenians]] ([[Armenians|Hayer]]): \n**[[Iranian peoples]]\n***[[East Iranian]] peoples\n****[[Northeast Iranian]] peoples\n*****[[Ossetians]] (Ir\u00e6\u0442\u0442\u00e6): [[Ossetia]] (Iryston), [[North Ossetia]] (C\u00e6gat Iryston), a Republic of [[Russia]], and [[South Ossetia]] (Khussar Iryston), a ''De Jure'' autonomous region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] (Sakartvelo), self-proclaimed sovereign country, North and South slopes of Central [[Caucasus]] Mountains.\n***[[West Iranian]] peoples\n****[[Southwestern Iranian languages|Southwest Iranian]] peoples\n*****[[Persian peoples]]\n******[[Tats (Caucasus)]] (Tati/Parsi/Lohijon/Daghli): East [[Caucasus]] Mountains, [[Azerbaijan]]\n*[[Kartvelian peoples]]\n**[[Zan people|Zan]]\n***[[Laz people|Lazs]] (Lazepe): Southwestern [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], Far Northeastern [[Turkey]]\n*[[Northeast Caucasian]] peoples\n**[[Avar-Andic languages|Avar-Andic]] peoples\n***[[Avar people (Caucasus)]] (Magharulal/Avaral): [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Andic languages|Andic]] peoples\n****[[Akhvakh people|Akhvakh]] (Ashvado/Atluatii)\n****[[Andi people|Andi]]s (Qhvannal/Khivannal)\n****[[Bagvalal people|Bagvalal]] (Bagval)\n****[[Botlikh people|Botlikh]]s (Buykhal'ida/Buykhalyi)\n****[[Chamalal people|Chamalal]]s (Chamalaldu)\n****[[Godoberi people|Godoberis]] (Giybdiridi)\n****[[Karata people|Karatas]] (Khkhiridi)\n****[[Tindi people|Tindis]] (Idarab)\n**[[Dargin people|Dargins]] (Darganti): [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n**[[Khinalug people|Khinalug]] (Kettiturdur/Kayttiodur/Ketid/Ketsh Khalkh)\n**[[Lak people (Dagestan)]]: [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n**[[Lezgic languages|Lezgic]] peoples\n***[[Aghul people|Aghul]] (Agular): [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Archi people|Archins]] (Arshishttib)\n***[[Budukh people|Budukh]] ([[Budukh people|Budad]])\n***[[Jek people|Jeks]] (Cekad/Dzhekad)\n***[[Kryts people|Kryts]] (Kh'rytsha'/Kyrtuar)\n***[[Lezgian people|Lezgians]] (Lezgiyar/Leqer): [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Rutul people|Rutul]] (Mykhabyr): [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Tabasaran people|Tabasarans]]: [[Dagestan]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Tsakhur people|Tsakhur]] (Yiqby): [[Azerbaijan]], Southern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[Udi people|Udins]] (Udi/Uti): Northern [[Azerbaijan]], Southern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n**[[Nakh peoples]]\n***[[Bats people|Bats]] (Batsbi)\n***[[Vainakh]] peoples\n****[[Chechens]] (Nokhchiy): [[Chechenia]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n****[[Ingush people|Ingush]] (Ghalghay): [[Ingushetia]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n**[[Tsezic languages|Tsezic]] (Didoic) peoples\n***[[Bezhta people|Bezhtas]]\n***[[Hinukh people|Hinukh]] (Hinuqes)\n***[[Hunzib people|Hunzibs]] (Hunzib)\n***[[Khwarshi people|Khwarshi]] (Khuani)\n***[[Tsez people|Tsez]]/[[Dido people]]\n*[[Northwest Caucasian]] peoples\n**[[Abkhaz-Abaza]] peoples\n***[[Abazins]] (Abaza)\n***[[Abkhazians]] (Aphsua): [[Abkhazia]] ([[Abkhazia|Aphsny]]) - a ''De Jure'' autonomous region of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] ([[Sakartvelo]]), self-proclaimed sovereign country.\n**[[Circassian People|Circassian peoples]]\n***[[West Circassian|West Circassian peoples]]\n****[[Adyghe people|Adyghe]] (Adyge): [[Adyghe Republic]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n***[[East Circassian]] peoples\n****[[Cherkess people|Cherkess]] (Cherkes): [[Karachay-Cherkessia]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n****[[Kabardians]] (Qeberdeykher): [[Kabardino-Balkaria]], [[European Russia]], Northern [[Caucasus]] Mountains\n**[[Ubykh people|Ubykh]] (T\u02b7a\u03c7): were indigenous to the mountains of West Caucasus, [[Sochi]] area, [[Krasnodar Krai]], [[Russia]], later migrated to [[Turkey]].\n\n===== Siberia =====\n[[File:Choris, Tschuktschen.jpg|thumb|Representation of a [[Chukchi people|Chukchi]] family by Louis Choris (1816)]]\n[[File:Khagdaev 02.jpg|thumb|[[Buryat people|Buryat]] [[shaman]] of [[Olkhon Island|Olkhon]], Lake Baikal in eastern Siberia.]]  \n[[File:Nenets Child.jpg|thumb|[[Nenets people|Nenets]] child]]\n\n*[[Northern indigenous peoples of Russia]]: Over 40 distinct peoples, each with their own language and culture in the Asiatic part of Russia ([[Siberia]]).\n**[[Chukchi-Kamchatkan]] peoples\n***[[Chukotkan]] peoples\n****[[Chukchi people|Chukchi]] (Lyg'oravetl'et/Chukchi people|O'ravetl'et/Ankalyn-Chavchu): Northeast [[Siberia]], Russia\n****[[Koryaks]] (Nymylan-Chauchuven): [[Russian Far East]]\n**[[Eskimo-Aleut peoples]]\n***[[Yupik peoples|Yupik]]: Alaska and the [[Russian Far East]]\n****[[Siberian Yupik]] (Yupighyt): [[Siberia]], Russia, [[Alaska]], [[United States]].\n*****[[Sirenik Eskimos]], [[Russian Far East]].\n*****[[Naukan people|Naukan]], [[Russian Far East]].\n**[[Mongolic languages|Mongolic peoples]]\n***Central Mongolic peoples\n****[[Buryats]] (Buryaad): [[Buryatia]], [[Russia]]\n**[[Tungusic peoples]]\n***Northern Tungusic peoples\n****[[Evenks]] (Evenkil): [[China]], [[Mongolia]], [[Russia]]\n****[[Udege people|Udege]] (Udihe/Udekhe/Udeghe): [[Russian Far East]], [[Ukraine]]\n**[[Turkic peoples]]\n***[[Siberian Turkic|Siberian Turks]]\n****[[Altay people|Altayans]] (Altay-kishi): Titular nation of [[Altai Republic]]\n****[[Khakas people|Khakas]] (Tadarlar):\n****[[Tuvans]] (Tyvalar): [[Tuva Republic]], close to the [[Altai Mountains]]\n****[[Yakut people|Yakuts]] (Sakha): [[Yakutia]], [[Siberia]], [[Russia]]\n****[[Dukha people|Dukha]] (Dukha/Dukhans/Duhalar/Tsaatan): [[Mongolia]]\n****[[Uriankhai]] (W\u016bli\u00e1ngh\u01cei/Uriankhan/\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043d\u0445\u0430\u043d/Uriankhat/\u0443\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043d\u0445\u0430\u0434): [[Mongolia]]\n***[[Kipchak Turks]]\n****[[Siberian Tatars]]\n****[[Baraba Tatars]]\n**[[Finno-Ugric peoples]]\n***[[Permians]] (on the basis of \"[[Siberia]]\" as a cultural region of Northern [[Eurasia]] that overlaps with Far North [[Eastern Europe]] in Far North [[European Russia]] and with parts of [[Northwest Europe]] in North [[Scandinavia]])\n****[[Komi peoples|Komi]] (Komiyas): [[Komi Republic]] in Northeast of [[European Russia]]\n****[[Udmurt people|Udmurts]] (Udmurt'yos): [[Udmurt Republic]] in Northeast of [[European Russia]]\n***[[Sami people|Sami]] (S\u00e1mi/Saami/Lapp): [[S\u00e1pmi]], Northern and central [[Norway]], Northern [[Sweden]], Northern [[Finland]] and [[Kola peninsula]] in the Northwest of [[Russia]]\n***[[Volga Finns]]\n****[[Mari people|Mari]] (Mari): Middle [[Volga]], [[European Russia]]\n****[[Mordvins]] (Erzyat/Mokshet): [[European Russia]]\n*****[[Erzyans]] (Erzyat)\n*****[[Moksha]] (Mokshet)\n***[[Ugrians]]: [[Yugra]], [[Siberia|Western Siberia]], Russia\n****[[Khanty people|Khanty]] (Hant\u00f5-Kant\u00f5k/Kantek/Khanti): [[Yugra]], [[Siberia|Western Siberia]], Russia\n****[[Mansi people|Mansi]] (Maan's'i/Maan's'i Maahum/Mansi), formerly known as [[Voguls]]: [[Yugra]], [[Siberia|Western Siberia]], Russia\n**[[Samoyedic peoples]]\n***Northern Samoyedic peoples: [[Siberia|West Siberia]] and Far Northern [[European Russia]]\n****[[Enets people|Enets]] (Entsi): Far Northern [[Siberia|Western Siberia]], Russia\n****[[Nenets people|Nenets]] (Neney Neneche): Far Northern [[Siberia|Western Siberia]] and Far Northern [[European Russia]]\n****[[Nganasan people|Nganasan]] (\u014a\u0259n\u0259hsa(n\u0259h)): [[Taymyr Peninsula]], [[Siberia]], Russia\n**[[Yukaghirs]] (Odul/Vadul/Detkil'): Far Northern [[East Siberia]], Russia\n**[[Yeniseian languages|Yeniseian]] peoples\n***[[Ket people|Ket]] (Deng): Along middle [[Yenisei river]] banks\n\n===== Eurasian Steppe =====\n[[File:111Pamiri1...jpg|250px|thumb|[[Pamiri people]] of [[Tajikistan]]]]\n\n*Indo-European peoples\n**[[Iranian peoples]]\n***[[East Iranians|East Iranian]] peoples\n****[[Northeast Iranian]] peoples\n*****[[Pamiris]] (Pomir): [[Badakhshan]] ([[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]]), [[Pamir Mountains]], [[Tashkurgan Tajik Autonomous County|Tashkurgan]] (in [[Xinjiang]])\n*****[[Tajiks]]: [[Tajikistan]]\n*****[[Yaghnobi people|Yaghnobi]] (Ya\u03b3n\u014db\u012b\u0301t): [[Tajikistan]]\n*[[Mongolic languages|Mongolic peoples]]\n**Central Mongolic peoples\n***[[Khoid]]: [[Mongolia]]\