 actress [[Nicolette Krebitz]], looking at the viewer through a worn out hole in her [[t-shirt]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Gillian Gilbert]], [[Peter Hook]], [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] and [[Bernard Sumner]]; except where indicated\n| headline        = CD #1: NUOCD09 (UK & Europe)\n\n| title1          = 60 Miles an Hour\n| note1           = radio edit\n| length1         = 3:50\n| title2          = Sabotage\n| length2         = 4:50\n| title3          = [[Someone Like You (New Order song)|Someone Like You]]\n| note3           = Funk D'Void Remix\n| length3         = 9:56\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = CD #2: NUCDP09 (UK & Europe)\n\n| title1          = 60 Miles an Hour\n| note1           = [[The Supermen Lovers|Supermen Lovers]] Remix\n| length1         = 4:56\n| title2          = [[Someone Like You (New Order song)|Someone Like You]]\n| note2           = [[James Holden (producer)|James Holden]] Heavy Dub\n| length2         = 6:56\n| title3          = [[Someone Like You (New Order song)|Someone Like You]]\n| note3           = Futureshock Vocal Remix\n| length3         = 8:05\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = CD: 0927434532 (Australia) - ''Tour EP''\n\n| title1          = 60 Miles an Hour\n| note1           = radio edit\n| length1         = 3:50\n| title2          = 60 Miles an Hour\n| note2           = [[The Supermen Lovers|Supermen Lovers]] Remix\n| length2         = 4:56\n| title3          = [[Someone Like You (New Order song)|Someone Like You]]\n| note3           = Funk D'Void Remix\n| length3         = 8:07\n| title4          = Sabotage\n| length4         = 4:50\n| title5          = [[True Faith (song)|True Faith]]\n| note5           = [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading Festival]] 30/08/98\n| writer5         = Gilbert, [[Stephen Hague]], Hook, Morris, Sumner\n| length5         = 5:40\n| title6          = [[Temptation (New Order song)|Temptation]]\n| note6           = [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading Festival]] 30/08/98\n| length6         = 7:27\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = DVD: NUDVD09 (UK)\n\n| title1          = 60 Miles an Hour (Radio Edit)\n| note1           = Audio\n| length1         = 3:50\n| title2          = Sabotage\n| note2           = Audio\n| length2         = 4:50\n| title3          = 60 Miles an Hour\n| note3           = Video\n| length3         = 3:59\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2001)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n| [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=occ>{{cite web|title=New Order - Full Official Chart History|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25394/new-order/|website=Official Charts Company|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 29\n|-\n!Chart (2002)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|[[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"ARIA\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=New+Order&titel=60+Miles+An+Hour&cat=s|title=australian-charts.com > New Order - 60 Miles An Hour|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2015-09-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 37\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|new-order|60-miles-an-hour}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{New Order}}\n\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:New Order (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bernard Sumner]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Peter Hook]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Morris (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gillian Gilbert]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:London Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Kahne]]\n", "name_user": "186.84.90.133", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/60_Miles_an_Hour"}
{"title_page": "Bizarre Love Triangle", "text_new": "{{short description|Song by the English rock band New Order}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| cover      = Blt_New_Order.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[New Order (band)|New Order]]\n| album      = [[Brotherhood (New Order album)|Brotherhood]]\n| released   = 5 November 1986<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=e1W6BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT318&lpg=PT318&dq=bizarre+love+triangle+5+november+1986&source=bl&ots=qBAxHMnzUz&sig=fjPA-6hmRSm_XJGfmimZI7jrwrg&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZx9DEt47QAhWCvRQKHRm8AkkQ6AEIMzAD#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Substance: Inside New Order |first=Peter |last=Hook |date=6 October 2016 |publisher=Simon & Schuster UK |accessdate=19 July 2017 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n| format     = {{flat list|\n* [[Phonograph record|7\"]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n}}\n| recorded   = January 1986<br><small>([[London]])</small>\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Alternative dance]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2016/09/scarlett-johanssons-band-sugar-for-sugar-covers-new-orders-bizarre-love-triangle-listen/|title=Scarlett Johansson's band Sugar for Sugar covers New Order's \"Bizarre Love Triangle\" -- listen|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/bizarre-love-triangle-mt0002928296|title=Bizarre Love Triangle - New Order |first=Stacia |last=Proefrock |work=AllMusic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/essential_guide_to_new_order | title=An Essential Guide to New Order | work=[[Exclaim!]] | date=8 September 2015 | accessdate=11 April 2016 |last=Lindsay |first=Cam}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 4:21 <small>(album version)</small><br>3:43 <small>(radio edit)</small><br>6:43 <small>(extended mix)</small>\n| label      = [[Factory Records|Factory]] <small>(FAC 163)</small>\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n* [[Gillian Gilbert]]\n* [[Peter Hook]]\n* [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]]\n* [[Bernard Sumner]]<ref name=\"ASCAP\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=320320630&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=25&start=1|title=ASCAP entry}}</ref>\n}}\n| producer   = New Order\n| prev_title = [[State of the Nation (New Order song)|State of the Nation]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[True Faith (song)|True Faith]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|tkOr12AQpnU|\"Bizarre Love Triangle{{popdf}}\u201d}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Bizarre Love Triangle'''\" is a song by the English [[Rock music|rock]] band [[New Order (band)|New Order]], released as a single in 1986 from their fourth studio album, ''[[Brotherhood (New Order album)|Brotherhood]]'' (1986), which reached the top five on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|US Hot Dance Music/Club Play Singles]] chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/new-order-mn0000334193|title=New Order - Music Biography, Streaming Radio and Discography - AllMusic|first=Jason|last=Ankeny|work=AllMusic}}</ref> and No. 5 on the Australian [[ARIA Charts]] (No. 1 on the [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] state chart) in March 1987.<ref name=aus>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|title=Australian Chart Book 1970-1992|year=1993 |publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, New South Wales, Australia|isbn=0-646-11917-6|pages=215}}</ref>\n\nIt failed to make the top 40 in either the United Kingdom (only reaching No. 56)<ref>[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/V%20Thirteen OfficialCharts.com] \"Bizarre Love Triangle\" UK chart history</ref> or the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In the United States, the song reached No. 8 on the Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales chart, but failed to chart on the Hot 100 during its original 1986 release. However, a new mix included on ''[[The Best of New Order]]'' was released in 1994 and finally made a brief appearance on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in the number 98 position in 1995.\n\nIn 2004 the song was ranked number 201 in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s \"[[List of Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Bernard Sumner]] - lead and backing vocals, synthesizers and programming\n*[[Peter Hook]] - bass, electronic percussion, programming\n*[[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] - drums, synthesizers and programming\n*[[Gillian Gilbert]] - synthesizers and programming\n\n==Releases==\nThe 12-inch version, remixed by [[Shep Pettibone]], also appears on the compilation ''[[Substance (New Order album)|Substance]]'' and a second remix by [[Stephen Hague]] features on their ''Best Of'' album. The original album version appears on the 2005 compilation ''[[Singles (New Order album)|Singles]]'', the 7-inch version appears on the 2016 reissue of this compilation. New Order's live versions since 1998 are based on the Shep Pettibone remix.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/apr04/articles/rogerlyons.htm |title=Recreating New Order's 'Blue Monday' Live |date=April 2004 |first=Tom |last=Flint |website=[[Sound on Sound]] |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe single mix features a cleaner sound with more electronics than the album version, notably the [[Fairlight CMI]] music workstation, the premier sampling keyboard workstation of the '80s, used to provide novel sounds, such as the [[orchestral hit]]s that were so popular, but also to sequence the song. All instruments except vocals and Peter Hook's melodic bass were sequenced (the song also prominently features synthesised bass and synth choir parts).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.keyboardmag.com/story.asp?storycode=10692 |title=New Order. New Album. Old School. All Good. |first=Stephen |last=Fortner |date=September 2005 |website=Keyboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051218235719/http://www.keyboardmag.com/story.asp?storycode=10692 |archivedate=18 December 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]], which was released in November 1986, was directed by [[United States|American]] artist [[Robert Longo]]. It prominently featured shots of a man and a woman in business suits flying through the air as though propelled by trampolines; this is based directly on Longo's \"Men in the Cities\" series of [[Lithography|lithographs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kinoteca.net/Text/Bizarre.htm |first=Michael |last=Shamberg |authorlink=Michael Shamberg |title=Bizarre Love Triangle |work=kinoteca.net |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060115071858/http://www.kinoteca.net/Text/Bizarre.htm |archivedate=15 January 2006}}</ref> The video also features a black and white cut-scene where [[Jodi Long]] and [[E. Max Frye]] are arguing about reincarnation, in which Long emphatically declares \"I don't believe in reincarnation because I refuse to come back as a bug or as a rabbit!\" Frye responds, \"You know, you're a real 'up' person,\" before the song resumes.\n\n==Cover versions==\n* \"Bizarre Love Triangle\" has been covered by many artists, such as [[Donna Lewis]], [[The Black Eyed Peas]], [[Even As We Speak]], Manitu, Commercial Breakup (by [[:w:de:Vredeber Albrecht|Vredeber Albrecht]]), [[Alison Statton|Devine and Statton]], [[Sita (singer)|Sita]], [[Tony DeSare]], [[South (British band)|South]], [[Rookie of the Year (band)|Rookie of the Year]], [[Apoptygma Berzerk]], [[Stabbing Westward]], [[Jaymay]], [[Charlotte Martin]], [[Anne Curtis]], [[Vendetta (German band)|Vendetta]], [[Nouvelle Vague (band)|Nouvelle Vague]], [[The Speaks]], [[Makana (musician)|Makana]], [[Echosmith]], [[Apostle of Hustle]], [[Glaiza de Castro]] and [[Zeus (band)|Zeus]].\n* Australian band [[Frente!]] released an acoustic cover version of the song in 1994, re-imagining it as a folk ballad. Issued as part of the ''[[Bizarre Love Triangle (Frente! EP)|Lonely]]'' EP in their home country, the cover peaked at number four on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Frente%21&titel=Accidently+Kelly+Street&cat=s \u2013 Frente! \u2013 Bizarre Love Triangle |publisher=[[ARIA Charts|ARIA Top 50 Singles]]|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> and became the band's only overseas hit, reaching number 49 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/frente/chart-history/hot-100|title=Frente! Chart History (Hot 100)|magazine=Billboard|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> number 53 in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.2505&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.2505.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.2505|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 2505|publisher=Library and Archives Canada|work=RPM|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> and number 76 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/32295/frente/|title=FRENTE Chart History|publisher=The Official UK Charts Company|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> In Australia it came in at number 63 on the 1994 year-end chart and was certified Gold for shipments of over 35,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/LHigR9p.jpg|title=The ARIA Australian Top 100 Singles 1994|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025122130/http://i.imgur.com/LHigR9p.jpg|archive-date=25 October 2015|access-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n* The song was also [[remix]]ed in 2005 by [[The Crystal Method]] (for their album ''[[Community Service II]]'') and by [[Richard X]] (for the New Order single \"[[Waiting for the Sirens' Call (song)|Waiting for the Sirens' Call]]\").\n* It was remade into Chinese with the Cantonese version by [[Amanda Lee (actress)|Amanda Lee]] and the Mandarin version, <!-- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D-Z050yba7M --> by [[Sandy Lam]], both under the title of \"\u4e00\u500b\u4eba / Y\u012b G\u00e8 R\u00e9n\" (\"Alone\").\n* American [[alternative rock]] band [[Nada Surf]] performed a version of the song in May 2012 for ''[[The A.V. Club]]''{{'s}} A.V. Undercover series.<ref name=\"undercover\">{{cite web |title=Nada Surf covers New Order |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/nada-surf-covers-new-order,70702/ |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref>\n* American [[alternative metal]] band [[New Years Day (band)|New Years Day]] covered the song on their 2018 EP ''Diary of a Creep''.\n* Canadian [[electronic music]] band [[Desire (band)|Desire]] covered the track in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/desire-cover-new-orders-bizarre-love-triangle |title=Desire Cover New Order's 'Bizarre Love Triangle' |last=Murray |first=Robin |date=14 February 2020 |website= clashmusic.com |publisher=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |access-date=21 February 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n* Chilean [[electronic music]] project PREZ covered the track in 2014.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Gillian Gilbert]], [[Peter Hook]], [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]], [[Bernard Sumner]]\n| headline        = 7\": FAC 163 (UK)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length1         = 3:43\n| title2          = Bizarre Dub Triangle\n| length2         = 3:23\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 7\": Qwest 7-28421 (US)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| note1           = edit\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = Every Little Counts\n| length2         = 4:29\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 7\": FAC-26 (Canada)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = Every Little Counts\n| length2         = 4:29\n}}\n* Initial pressings (matrix FAC-26-A) were the UK 7\" mix,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/New-Order-Bizarre-Love-Triangle/release/2530184 |title=New Order - Bizarre Love Triangle |website=Discogs |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref> later pressings (matrix FAC-26-A2) were the Canadian 7\" mix<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/release/505366 |title=New Order - Bizarre Love Triangle |website=Discogs |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 7\": FAC-163153 (Australia)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = [[State of the Nation (New Order song)|State of the Nation]]\n| length2         = 3:27\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 12\": FAC 163 (UK)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length1         = 6:44\n| title2          = Bizarre Dub Triangle\n| length2         = 7:02\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 12\": Qwest 0-20546 (US)\n\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length1         = 6:41\n| title2          = I Don't Care\n| note2           = Actually \"Bizarre Dub Triangle\"\n| length2         = 7:02\n| title3          = [[State of the Nation (New Order song)|State of the Nation]]\n| length3         = 6:31\n| title4          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| length4         = 3:43\n}}\n* US editions mis-credit \"Bizarre Dub Triangle\" as \"I Don't Care\", reputedly due to a record company person contacting New Order's Manager Rob Gretton to ask what to name the mix as, Gretton is claimed to have said \"I don't care\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neworder-recycle.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/recycle-13-bizarre-love-triangle.html |title=Recycle 13: Bizarre Love Triangle |date=5 September 2009 |work=neworder-recycle.blogspot |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006071852/http://neworder-recycle.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/recycle-13-bizarre-love-triangle.html |archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n{{track listing\n| headline        = CD: Qwest 9 20546-2 (US) - released in 1994\n| title1          = Bizarre Love Triangle\n| note1           = album version\n| le