{"title_page": "The Perfect Kiss", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Perfect Kiss\n| cover      = Perfectkiss.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[New Order (band)|New Order]]\n| album      = [[Low-Life]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"The Kiss of Death\"|\"Perfect Pit\"}}\n| released   = 13 May 1985\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]], [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   = 1984\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/live-reviews/new-order-play-with-their-pleasure-zones-in-joyous-new-york-city-show-20160311|title=New Order Play With Their Pleasure Zones in Joyous New York City Show|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|date=11 March 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n*[[alternative dance]]<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/low-life-mw0000650557 |title=''Low-Life'' \u2013 New Order |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=23 January 2013 |last=Bush |first=John}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 4:48 <small>(Album version)</small><br>8:46 <small>(Full version)</small>\n| label      = [[Factory Records|Factory]] - <small>FAC 123</small>\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Gillian Gilbert]]\n*[[Peter Hook]]\n*[[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]]\n*[[Bernard Sumner]]<ref>[http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=460249258&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=25&start=1 ASCAP entry]</ref>\n}}\n| producer   = New Order\n| prev_title = [[Murder (song)|Murder]]\n| prev_year  = 1984\n| next_title = [[Sub-culture (song)|Sub-culture]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n}}\n\n\"'''The Perfect Kiss'''\" is a song by the English [[alternative dance]] and [[Rock music|rock]] band [[New Order (band)|New Order]]. It was recorded at [[Britannia Row Studios]] in London and released on 13 May 1985.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Lee |date=2012-03-29 |title= GQ&A: BERNARD SUMNER|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/bernard-sumner-interview-2012-new-order|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref> It is the first New Order song to be included on a [[studio album]], ''[[Low-Life]]'', at the same time as its release as a single. The vinyl version has Factory catalogue number FAC 123 and the video has the opposite number, FAC 321.\n\n==Background==\nWhile widely regarded as a centrepiece of New Order's catalogue, \"The Perfect Kiss\" reached only number 46 in the UK charts. \n\nThe song's themes include love \"We believe in a land of love\" and death \"the perfect kiss is the kiss of death\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lariviere |first=Aaron |date=2013-01-25 |title=The 10 Best New Order Songs|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1244332/the-10-best-new-order-songs/top-stories/|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Billboard-Hollywood Reporter Media Group |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref> The overall meaning of the song is unclear to its writer today. In an interview with ''GQ'' magazine [[Bernard Sumner]] said \"I haven't a clue what this is about.\" He agreed with the interviewer that his best known lyric is in the song: \"Pretending not to see his gun/I said, 'Let's go out and have some fun'\". The lyrics, he added, came about after the band was visiting a man's house in the United States who showed his guns under his bed before they went out for an enjoyable night. It had been quickly written, recorded and mixed without sleep before the band went on tour in Australia.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Lee |date=2012-03-29 |title= GQ&A: BERNARD SUMNER|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/bernard-sumner-interview-2012-new-order|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe song's complex arrangement includes a number of instruments and methods not normally used by New Order. For example, a bridge features [[frog]]s croaking melodically. The band reportedly included them because Morris loved the effect and was looking for any excuse to use it. At the end of the track, the faint bleating of a (synthesized) sheep can be heard. Sheep samples would reappear in later New Order singles \"[[Fine Time]]\" and \"[[Ruined in a Day]]\". \n\nDespite being a fan favourite, the song was not performed live between 1993 and 2006 due to the complexity of converting the programs from the [[E-mu]] Emulator to the new [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] synthesizer. However, it returned to the live set at a performance in [[Athens]] on 3 June 2006.\n\n==Sleeve==\nThe [[Peter Saville (graphic designer)|Peter Saville]] sleeve is uniform silver with the word \"perfect\" embossed on the front side and \"kiss The\" on the back, like a wraparound band. It was about this time that the photographer Geoff Power [see \"[[Shellshock (song)|Shellshock]]\"] was introduced to Saville. So enamoured was Saville by Power's work that he originally offered the photographer the cover to ''Low-Life''. Then when that fell through, they worked on a cover for \"The Perfect Kiss\" using one of Power's photographs, which can be seen later in New Order's songbook, 'X'. With time running out and Saville's decision not to run with this image \u2013 it didn't fit in his subsequent portraits of the band on ''Low-Life'' \u2013 Power was offered an OMD album cover instead. Power decided to use the image for the New Order release, ''[[Shellshock (song)|Shellshock]]'', a year later.\n\n==Versions==\nLasting nearly 9 minutes, the full 12\" single version of the song is longer than even \"[[Blue Monday (New Order song)|Blue Monday]]\", New Order's 1983 dance epic. This version also appears on the vinyl edition of ''[[Substance 1987|Substance]]'', with the CD pressings deleting 44 seconds of the climactic finale, due to time limitations of the CD format in 1987 (future remasterings of ''Substance'' did not restore the missing 44 seconds, even though newer CDs would allow for it). The full version was eventually released unedited on the 2-disc deluxe edition of ''Low-Life'', marking its first appearance on CD.\n\nThe version on the original ''[[Low-Life]]'' and all post-''Substance'' compilations is a 4:48 edit that omits the third verse (the one that mentions the song's title) and fades out before the climax. This version is present on the A-side of the 7\" single from the Philippines; most 7\" issues from other countries have on the A-side a version that is further edited to 4:24 (in some or all cases without the percussion introduction). The UK 7\" promo release on Factory Records is a rarely heard edit cut by Ivan Ivan which compresses most of the elements of the full, 8:46 version (including the ending but not the third verse) into 3:50.\n\nThere is also a pre-edited recording of the live performance filmed for the music video with later overdubbed mistakes left intact; it is available on the bonus disc included with some editions of ''[[Retro (New Order album)|Retro]]'' and on various promotional vinyl releases.\n\nThe song has been remixed by third parties like [[Razormaid]] and Hot Tracks and has been covered by bands including Capsule Giants, Nude,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.neworderonline.com/Music/Song.aspx?SongID=55\n|title=neworderonline.com\n|accessdate=2007-10-17\n}}, song browser entry for \"The Perfect Kiss\"</ref>\nInternational,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.neworderonline.com/Common/Topic.aspx?Topic=InternationalBand\n|title=neworderonline.com\n|accessdate=2007-10-17\n}}, band bio for International</ref>\n[[Paradoxx]], Razed in a New Division of Agony,\nand Amoeba Crunch.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.amoebacrunch.com/L9123.html\n |title       = amoebacrunch.com\n |work        = The Perfect Kiss\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-17\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140813141741/http://amoebacrunch.com/L9123.html\n |archivedate = 2014-08-13\n}}</ref>\n\n==B-sides==\n\"The Kiss of Death\" is a typical New Order dub version: it is a mostly instrumental [[remix]] of the A-side with added effects; it notably features the opening of the [[Low-Life|album version]]. \"Perfect Pit\" is a short recording of synthesized bass and drum parts that sounds like [[Gillian Gilbert]] and [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] practicing.\n\n==Music video==\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Perfect Kiss\n| image = \n| caption = \n| director = [[Jonathan Demme]]\n| producer = [[Michael Shamberg]]\n| screenplay = \n| starring = [[New Order (band)|New Order]]\n| music = New Order\n| cinematography = [[Henri Alekan]]\n| editing = [[Tony Lawson]]\n| studio = Factory Films\n| distributor = [[Palace Pictures]]\n| released = Sept 1985\n| runtime = 11 minutes\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n}}\n\n[[Jonathan Demme]] directed \"The Perfect Kiss\" video, which is unlike any other New Order clip. Set in the band's practice room, it simply depicts the band playing the song from beginning to end. According to [[Factory Records]] owner [[Tony Wilson]], Demme was looking forward to filming dynamic shots of Stephen Morris behind the drum kit and was dismayed to find that the drums in the song were all programmed.\n\nThe video features a Joy Division poster for 'Unknown Pleasures' that can be prominently seen behind Bernard Sumner.\n\nThe video appeared on the ''Substance 1989'' [[VHS]] tape and the DVD ''A Collection''. An edit of the video version appeared on a US 12\" single in 1985. The full audio take, including Demme's remarks before and after the performance, appeared on a bonus CD included with early copies of the box set ''Retro''. Since it is a unique live performance, the video version of the song sounds different from other released versions.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Gillian Gilbert]], [[Peter Hook]], [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] and [[Bernard Sumner]]\n| headline        = 12: FAC 123 (UK) / Qwest 9 20330-0 (US)\n\n| title1          = The Perfect Kiss\n| length1         = 8:46\n| title2          = Kiss of Death\n| length2         = 7:02\n| title3          = Perfect Pit\n| length3         = 1:24\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 7\": FAC 123 (UK)\n\n| title1          = The Perfect Kiss\n| length1         = 3:51\n| title2          = Kiss of Death\n| length2         = 3:01\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (1985)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]]<ref name=aus>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|title=Australian Chart Book 1970-1992|year=1993 |publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, NSW, Australia|isbn=0-646-11917-6|pages=215}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|85\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Irish Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|RIANZ]] Singles Chart\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|46\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Independent Singles and Albums Charts|UK Indie Singles]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|x3XW6NLILqo|Music video}}\n\n{{New Order}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perfect Kiss, The}}\n[[Category:New Order (band) songs]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bernard Sumner]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Peter Hook]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Morris (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gillian Gilbert]]\n[[Category:Factory Records singles]]\n[[Category:1984 songs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Perfect Kiss\n| cover      = Perfectkiss.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[New Order (band)|New Order]]\n| album      = [[Low-Life]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"The Kiss of Death\"|\"Perfect Pit\"}}\n| released   = 13 May 1985\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]], [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   = 1984\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/live-reviews/new-order-play-with-their-pleasure-zones-in-joyous-new-york-city-show-20160311|title=New Order Play With Their Pleasure Zones in Joyous New York City Show|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|date=11 March 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref>\n*[[dance-pop]]<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/low-life-mw0000650557 |title=''Low-Life'' \u2013 New Order |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=23 January 2013 |last=Bush |first=John}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 4:48 <small>(Album version)</small><br>8:46 <small>(Full version)</small>\n| label      = [[Factory Records|Factory]] - <small>FAC 123</small>\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Gillian Gilbert]]\n*[[Peter Hook]]\n*[[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]]\n*[[Bernard Sumner]]<ref>[http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=460249258&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=25&start=1 ASCAP entry]</ref>\n}}\n| producer   = New Order\n| prev_title = [[Murder (song)|Murder]]\n| prev_year  = 1984\n| next_title = [[Sub-culture (song)|Sub-culture]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n}}\n\n\"'''The Perfect Kiss'''\" is a song by the English [[alternative dance]] and [[Rock music|rock]] band [[New Order (band)|New Order]]. It was recorded at [[Britannia Row Studios]] in London and released on 13 May 1985.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Lee |date=2012-03-29 |title= GQ&A: BERNARD SUMNER|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/bernard-sumner-interview-2012-new-order|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref> It is the first New Order song to be included on a [[studio album]], ''[[Low-Life]]'', at the same time as its release as a single. The vinyl version has Factory catalogue number FAC 123 and the video has the opposite number, FAC 321.\n\n==Background==\nWhile widely regarded as a centrepiece of New Order's catalogue, \"The Perfect Kiss\" reached only number 46 in the UK charts. \n\nThe song's themes include love \"We believe in a land of love\" and death \"the perfect kiss is the kiss of death\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Lariviere |first=Aaron |date=2013-01-25 |title=The 10 Best New Order Songs|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1244332/the-10-best-new-order-songs/top-stories/|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Billboard-Hollywood Reporter Media Group |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref> The overall meaning of the song is unclear to its writer today. In an interview with ''GQ'' magazine [[Bernard Sumner]] said \"I haven't a clue what this is about.\" He agreed with the interviewer that his best known lyric is in the song: \"Pretending not to see his gun/I said, 'Let's go out and have some fun'\". The lyrics, he added, came about after the band was visiting a man's house in the United States who showed his guns under his bed before they went out for an enjoyable night. It had been quickly written, recorded and mixed without sleep before the band went on tour in Australia.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gale |first=Lee |date=2012-03-29 |title= GQ&A: BERNARD SUMNER|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/bernard-sumner-interview-2012-new-order|magazine= |location=New York City|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe song's complex arrangement includes a number of instruments and methods not normally used by New Order. For example, a bridge features [[frog]]s croaking melodically. The band reportedly included them because Morris loved the effect and was looking for any excuse to use it. At the end of the track, the faint bleating of a (synthesized) sheep can be heard. Sheep samples would reappear in later New Order singles \"[[Fine Time]]\" and \"[[Ruined in a Day]]\". \n\nDespite being a fan favourite, the song was not performed live between 1993 and 2006 due to the complexity of converting the programs from the [[E-mu]] Emulator to the new [[Roland Corporation|Roland]] synthesizer. However, it returned to the live set at a performance in [[Athens]] on 3 June 2006.\n\n==Sleeve==\nThe [[Peter Saville (graphic designer)|Peter Saville]] sleeve is uniform silver with the word \"perfect\" embossed on the front side and \"kiss The\" on the back, like a wraparound band. It was about this time that the photographer Geoff Power [see \"[[Shellshock (song)|Shellshock]]\"] was introduced to Saville. So enamoured was Saville by Power's work that he originally offered the photographer the cover to ''Low-Life''. Then when that fell through, they worked on a cover for \"The Perfect Kiss\" using one of Power's photographs, which can be seen later in New Order's songbook, 'X'. With time running out and Saville's decision not to run with this image \u2013 it didn't fit in his subsequent portraits of the band on ''Low-Life'' \u2013 Power was offered an OMD album cover instead. Power decided to use the image for the New Order release, ''[[Shellshock (song)|Shellshock]]'', a year later.\n\n==Versions==\nLasting nearly 9 minutes, the full 12\" single version of the song is longer than even \"[[Blue Monday (New Order song)|Blue Monday]]\", New Order's 1983 dance epic. This version also appears on the vinyl edition of ''[[Substance 1987|Substance]]'', with the CD pressings deleting 44 seconds of the climactic finale, due to time limitations of the CD format in 1987 (future remasterings of ''Substance'' did not restore the missing 44 seconds, even though newer CDs would allow for it). The full version was eventually released unedited on the 2-disc deluxe edition of ''Low-Life'', marking its first appearance on CD.\n\nThe version on the original ''[[Low-Life]]'' and all post-''Substance'' compilations is a 4:48 edit that omits the third verse (the one that mentions the song's title) and fades out before the climax. This version is present on the A-side of the 7\" single from the Philippines; most 7\" issues from other countries have on the A-side a version that is further edited to 4:24 (in some or all cases without the percussion introduction). The UK 7\" promo release on Factory Records is a rarely heard edit cut by Ivan Ivan which compresses most of the elements of the full, 8:46 version (including the ending but not the third verse) into 3:50.\n\nThere is also a pre-edited recording of the live performance filmed for the music video with later overdubbed mistakes left intact; it is available on the bonus disc included with some editions of ''[[Retro (New Order album)|Retro]]'' and on various promotional vinyl releases.\n\nThe song has been remixed by third parties like [[Razormaid]] and Hot Tracks and has been covered by bands including Capsule Giants, Nude,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.neworderonline.com/Music/Song.aspx?SongID=55\n|title=neworderonline.com\n|accessdate=2007-10-17\n}}, song browser entry for \"The Perfect Kiss\"</ref>\nInternational,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.neworderonline.com/Common/Topic.aspx?Topic=InternationalBand\n|title=neworderonline.com\n|accessdate=2007-10-17\n}}, band bio for International</ref>\n[[Paradoxx]], Razed in a New Division of Agony,\nand Amoeba Crunch.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.amoebacrunch.com/L9123.html\n |title       = amoebacrunch.com\n |work        = The Perfect Kiss\n |accessdate  = 2007-10-17\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140813141741/http://amoebacrunch.com/L9123.html\n |archivedate = 2014-08-13\n}}</ref>\n\n==B-sides==\n\"The Kiss of Death\" is a typical New Order dub version: it is a mostly instrumental [[remix]] of the A-side with added effects; it notably features the opening of the [[Low-Life|album version]]. \"Perfect Pit\" is a short recording of synthesized bass and drum parts that sounds like [[Gillian Gilbert]] and [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] practicing.\n\n==Music video==\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Perfect Kiss\n| image = \n| caption = \n| director = [[Jonathan Demme]]\n| producer = [[Michael Shamberg]]\n| screenplay = \n| starring = [[New Order (band)|New Order]]\n| music = New Order\n| cinematography = [[Henri Alekan]]\n| editing = [[Tony Lawson]]\n| studio = Factory Films\n| distributor = [[Palace Pictures]]\n| released = Sept 1985\n| runtime = 11 minutes\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n}}\n\n[[Jonathan Demme]] directed \"The Perfect Kiss\" video, which is unlike any other New Order clip. Set in the band's practice room, it simply depicts the band playing the song from beginning to end. According to [[Factory Records]] owner [[Tony Wilson]], Demme was looking forward to filming dynamic shots of Stephen Morris behind the drum kit and was dismayed to find that the drums in the song were all programmed.\n\nThe video features a Joy Division poster for 'Unknown Pleasures' that can be prominently seen behind Bernard Sumner.\n\nThe video appeared on the ''Substance 1989'' [[VHS]] tape and the DVD ''A Collection''. An edit of the video version appeared on a US 12\" single in 1985. The full audio take, including Demme's remarks before and after the performance, appeared on a bonus CD included with early copies of the box set ''Retro''. Since it is a unique live performance, the video version of the song sounds different from other released versions.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Gillian Gilbert]], [[Peter Hook]], [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] and [[Bernard Sumner]]\n| headline        = 12: FAC 123 (UK) / Qwest 9 20330-0 (US)\n\n| title1          = The Perfect Kiss\n| length1         = 8:46\n| title2          = Kiss of Death\n| length2         = 7:02\n| title3          = Perfect Pit\n| length3         = 1:24\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = 7\": FAC 123 (UK)\n\n| title1          = The Perfect Kiss\n| length1         = 3:51\n| title2          = Kiss of Death\n| length2         = 3:01\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (1985)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]]<ref name=aus>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=David|title=Australian Chart Book 1970-1992|year=1993 |publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, NSW, Australia|isbn=0-646-11917-6|pages=215}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|85\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Irish Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|RIANZ]] Singles Chart\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|46\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Independent Singles and Albums Charts|UK Indie Singles]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|x3XW6NLILqo|Music video}}\n\n{{New Order}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perfect Kiss, The}}\n[[Category:New Order (band) songs]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bernard Sumner]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Peter Hook]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Morris (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gillian Gilbert]]\n[[Category:Factory Records singles]]\n[[Category:1984 songs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "name_user": "186.84.90.133", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Perfect_Kiss"}
